    "explanation": "Diagram 1 depicts a high-level architecture of a media streaming and download system, focusing on network infrastructure and storage. It illustrates external users accessing media streams and initiating downloads via an internet router, which interfaces with a NAS (Network Attached Storage) subnet. This subnet houses the NAS server, a container pool, a download queue API server, and the storage volume. A firewall protects the setup. Diagram 2 dives into the software architecture of a web-based download system, detailing the interaction between the user, web browser, web server components like REST API, authentication handler, queue manager, download worker, and data stores. It showcases the user's interaction from accessing the login page, submitting credentials, to downloading files from a source (YouTube in this case). WebSocket communication is used for real-time updates. The architecture follows a layered approach with distinct frontend (Web Browser) and backend (Web Server) components. Both diagrams address download functionality, but Diagram 1 emphasizes the hardware and network aspects of serving the media. At the same time, Diagram 2 focuses on the software components and workflow of the download process. They both illustrate a system that deals with download requests (media streams in diagram 1, general downloads in diagram 2). The two diagrams are highly different and it is difficult to compare them due to the different levels of abstraction. Diagram 1 is a high-level infrastructure diagram, while diagram 2 is a detailed software architecture diagram. Diagram 2 is clearly the better diagram because of the level of detail that it contains, this diagram gives a very good explanation of the system. I would give diagram 1 a score of 4/10 and diagram 2 a score of 9/10."
